---
description: Multi-tenant data isolation — this app serves many apartments/societies, not one
alwaysApply: true
---
- This is a multi-tenant SaaS. Every apartment/society is a separate tenant.
  A "society" row is the tenant boundary — every other table (flats,
  residents, invoices, complaints, expenses, vendors, quotations) must have
  a society_id column, no exceptions.
- Never write a query against a tenant-scoped table without filtering by
  society_id. If you're about to write one "just for this internal script,"
  stop — there's no such thing as an internal script that skips this.
- Enforce tenant isolation at the database level with Postgres Row-Level
  Security (RLS) policies, not just app-layer WHERE clauses. App-layer
  filtering is a second line of defense, not the primary one — a single
  missed WHERE clause should not be able to leak one society's data to
  another.
- Two distinct admin tiers, don't conflate them:
  - platform superadmin (you) — manages societies themselves, can see
    cross-tenant data for support/billing purposes only.
  - society admin — manages only their own society, has zero visibility
    into other societies, even that they exist.
- Every society gets a unique slug (e.g. greenview-apartments) used for
  routing/access — plan the column now even if subdomain routing isn't
  built until later.

  ---
description: Auth and financial data handling — load for anything touching login, roles, or payments
alwaysApply: false
---
- Passwords: bcrypt/argon2 hashed, never stored or logged in plaintext.
- JWT or session-based auth — either is fine, but be consistent, and store
  role in the token/session, re-verify role server-side on every request.
- Payment gateway is Cashfree, using **Easy Split** — each society has its
  own Cashfree vendor id tied to its own bank details. Maintenance payments
  must be split to the correct society's vendor, never pooled into one
  central account. Get the vendor id from the society's record before
  creating any payment order.
- Never trust client-side "payment success" callbacks alone — an invoice
  is only marked paid after Cashfree's webhook confirms it server-side,
  with signature verification on every webhook payload.
- Cashfree credentials (client id / client secret) live in server-side env
  vars only — never in client/ code, never committed to git.
- Webhook handler must be idempotent (Cashfree can retry/resend the same
  event) — check payment/order id before applying an update twice.
- Never expose other residents' contact/vehicle details across flats unless
  the requester is manager/admin/staff.